00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:38.000
We can see that higher amounts of green indicate lower carbon intensity,

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:46.000
and higher amounts of brown mean fossil fuels and higher amounts of CO2 intensity overall.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:49.000
We see that in this column. We see that in these columns.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:56.000
And this is basically a really nice table that's improved by adding color to the table.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:01.000
So a few different methods will be used, but not too many, surprisingly, for this large table.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:05.000
We will add, of course, a table title with a tab header.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:09.000
But the new thing that we'll show here is we can add source notes at the bottom of the table.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:13.000
This is the footer section of the table with tab source note.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:18.000
We will change the width of the different columns with the calls width method.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:22.000
We have a lot of percentage values in the table, and that'll just be formatted with format percent.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:28.000
In quite a few uses of data underscore color, we will color different subsets of the table.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:34.000
So there'll be different treatments of color as we move across the table with data color.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:43.000
And then finally, we will align values away from their default alignment with the calls align method.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:50.000
So let me show you what tab source note and calls width does.

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:53.000
So we can add notes to the table in a footer component.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:57.000
This is similar to adding a title in terms of how it operates.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:00.000
But we're adding it to the bottom, and these are table notes.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:03.000
We'll do that with the tab source note method.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:11.000
So using our example table, we'll just use GT, of course, to encapsulate that and to make that table.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:16.000
We'll add a source note with tab source note, and we'll just provide a bit of text called note.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:20.000
And we'll see that at the bottom of the table right here.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:25.000
And the thing that we can do to change the width of columns,

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:32.000
because sometimes you might want to take control of the column widths, is to use the calls width method.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:38.000
We can do that by providing a set of cases in a dictionary, providing the column name,

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:41.000
and then, like, widths in pixel values.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:43.000
And we can do also other things, too.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:45.000
We can also use percentage values.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:53.000
Basically anything that HTML tables accepts in terms of CSS length units are accepted here.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:54.000
Okay.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:03:00.000
So we see that when the table widths are determined by content size,

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:05.000
we get this tight packing of columns and values together.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:07.000
These are the default widths.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:10.000
But we just customize them by providing that dictionary of values.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:14.000
And so we see here that this column here is 150px, this one here is 100px,

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:22.000
and this date column is 200px, just as we provided in that calls width column.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:27.000
So in the table, sorry, in the notebook that we use later,

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:33.000
we go through that in the sections tab source note and calls width.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:38.000
So data color is a method that we use to apply color to tables.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:43.000
And it serves us sort of like making a heat map in a table.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:48.000
And to do that, we provide a palette, the columns that we want to apply it to,

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:53.000
and also the range of values that the palette is going to span over.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:59.000
So, yeah, it really makes this large amount of information here much easier to digest at a glance.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:04.000
So you can see that large values can be seen right away because they have a really intense color value.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:10.000
And in some cases, negligible values, like things which are very close to zero, they lack color.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:14.000
So that's really nice to see.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:21.000
So we get two advantages from plots in tables from doing it from providing heat maps in tables.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:25.000
We emphasize differences in values, and we also reveal trends in the data.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:28.000
So for instance, here, we have this one row.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:34.000
We can scan across this row and see that, in this case, nuclear is the dominant form of energy in France,

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:39.000
just by looking at the color. We didn't even have to look at the value.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:43.000
And column-wise, we can compare across observations.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:47.000
If we're just looking at CO2 intensity, we can see that the top values here, they're ranked,

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:54.000
but we can just see by color that these are the lowest CO2 intensity values.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:59.000
And if we see these as a trend, we can see a global pattern of values in the table.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:06.000
So the trend I see here is that more energy from columns to the right leads to higher CO2 intensity values.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:13.000
We see a sweep from top left to bottom right in terms of high amounts of green on the top left

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:18.000
and large amounts of darker brown on the bottom right.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:21.000
So data color is pretty easy to use initially.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:25.000
We can actually use it without any supplied arguments at all to colorize a GT table.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:31.000
If you just take an exible, pass out the GT, and then use data color without any arguments,

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:37.000
we get all the columns which are colored in different ways, which is not really desirable.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:39.000
We don't really want a table like this.

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:45.000
So what's more often the case is we supply certain columns along with a palette.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:51.000
So in this case, the num and the currency columns will receive colorization,

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:54.000
and we see here that they go from red to green.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:58.000
So red is like the lowest values, and green are the highest values.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:01.000
They're in order here, but they're out of order here.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:03.000
So we sort of see that right there.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:06.000
This is good, but not quite so good.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:14.000
Another way to do it is to constrain the cells which the coloring can be applied to.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:18.000
So we do that, of course, you saw with columns, but we can also constrain the rows.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:22.000
Sometimes you don't want these very large values to be included for whatever reason.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:24.000
We can do that just by selecting certain rows.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:30.000
In this case, it's a pandas data frame, so we can use a lambda here to only color the values

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:33.000
where the currency value is less than 50.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:36.000
So to resolve this expression.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:40.000
Another thing we're doing here is we're choosing a domain.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:43.000
So we're actually setting the limits of the colorization.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:46.000
So zero to 50, that's what we'll use for coloring,

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:50.000
and anything outside of that will just not be used.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:51.000
Okay.

