00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:36.000
I'll comment this code and then use data color.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:37.000
Great.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:42.000
The columns in this case will be a larger set of columns.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:44.000
I have it as a list here.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:49.000
I didn't show you this before, but you can just have a list of columns.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:51.000
And I'll have to use a selector because it's actually a little bit complex

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:55.000
to use a selector here because nothing is really common across these columns

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:57.000
in terms of their naming.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:58.000
Great.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:16:59.000
Columns.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:01.000
And then the next argument is palette.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:03.000
And I have a palette, which is right here.

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:05.000
So I will copy that in.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:06.000
Great.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:08.000
And then finally, domain.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:12.000
In this case, I've written that I wanted it to be from 0 to 1

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:14.000
because these are fractional values.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:16.000
So that is the domain there.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:18.000
So I'm going to run this.

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:23.000
And we see that we do have either very light green or dark green values here,

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:26.000
depending on how high it is in the range from 0 to 1,

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:30.000
or in this case, 0% to 100%.

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:31.000
Okay.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:34.000
We do the same thing for the biomass column, just that one column.

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:40.000
So this is pretty much going to be another data color column right here.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:44.000
Data color columns is the argument we need.

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:47.000
And it's just one column, biomass.

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:50.000
And then it's going to be the palette.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:54.000
Palette is right here, snow to this other color,

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:58.000
which I'm not very good at reading hexadecimal color values,

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:00.000
but I'm assuming that's going to be brown.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:02.000
And then we're going to have a range,

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:08.000
which is going to be represented by the domain from 0 to 0.3.

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:10.000
There we are.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:14.000
Running that cell, we can see that right here

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:19.000
we have the biomass column colored much differently than these columns right here.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:20.000
Great.

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:24.000
So now we have a few more to do.

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:30.000
In this case, we want gas to oil to be this palette right here, which we have,

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:33.000
which is pretty similar to the other palette.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:36.000
So data color.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:39.000
It's going to have certain columns.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:45.000
And in this case, it's going to be gas, coal, and oil.

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:48.000
I'm just going to type those in.

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:54.000
Gas, coal, oil.

00:18:54.000 --> 00:19:01.000
The palette in this case will be this palette.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:03.000
Great.

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:09.000
And then we're going to have a domain of 0 to 1.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:11.000
That's a list of two items.

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:12.000
There we are.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:14.000
Going to run that cell as well.

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:16.000
Okay, and we see it right away.

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:18.000
It's these columns right here.

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:19.000
There we are.

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:23.000
And then finally, we're going to ensure the remaining cells have the snow color applied.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:27.000
They're not going to have any sort of data color.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:29.000
Well, we're actually going to use data color.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:30.000
We're going to use a trick of it.

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:32.000
We're not going to move between multiple colors.

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:36.000
We're just going to apply the one color.

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:41.000
So the remaining columns are going to be zone up to battery discharge.

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:45.000
So I'm going to type in data color.

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:49.000
Columns, zone to battery discharge.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:55.000
And then in this case, the palette is going to be the same color repeated twice.

00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:58.000
Snow and snow.

00:19:58.000 --> 00:19:59.000
Okay.

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:02.000
So the reason this works is two colors is what's needed as a minimum,

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:04.000
but we're not changing the value.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:06.000
So we don't even need a domain.

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:09.000
Essentially, it's going to be the same color for all these columns.

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:13.000
Zone up towards battery discharge altogether.

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:15.000
I'm going to run that cell.

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:16.000
Great.

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:20.000
And because snow is so similar to the background, we barely see a difference,

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:24.000
but the difference is there upon closer inspection.

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:26.000
Great.

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:34.000
So now what we want to do is align all the values in these cells to be centered.

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:36.000
Right here.

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:37.000
It's a stylistic choice.

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:41.000
You don't often center numeric values,

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:44.000
but in this case we're just going to go for it and do it because we can.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:48.000
So to do that, we'll use calls align.

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:52.000
And then the first argument for that is align.

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:56.000
And in this case, we want to use center.

00:20:56.000 --> 00:20:57.000
Okay.

00:20:57.000 --> 00:20:59.000
Great.

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:03.000
And then the second argument will be which columns do you want to center?

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:06.000
So there's a cool little trick in pollers where you can select all the columns

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:12.000
by using kl.call and then in quotes and asterisks.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:17.000
So this just means that every column we'll have will be targeted here.

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:19.000
So let's run that.

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:23.000
And we see from the table that we do have every value centered,

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:26.000
including these text values, which doesn't look so good.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:28.000
So why should we tweak that?

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:32.000
Well, as a separate thing, we'll use calls align again.

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:34.000
And maybe we'll just move it back.

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:37.000
So it'll be calls align.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:41.000
Align will be left.

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:45.000
And columns in this case will be zone.

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:46.000
Great.

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:48.000
So running that, we see that zone is back to the left,

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:53.000
but everything else is centered because we just did a tweak on one column.

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:54.000
Great.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:59.000
Now for this table, I want to use, again, the humanist font stack.

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:05.000
And to do that, we use the opt table font method.

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:07.000
So I'm going to type that in.

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:09.000
Opt table font.

00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:10.000
There we are.

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:13.000
There's an argument for that called stack.

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:17.000
And we just have to provide the name, humanist, as a string.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:21.000
And in doing so and running the cell, we see that the font did change.

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:25.000
It has quite a bit of a different look compared to before.

00:22:25.000 --> 00:22:27.000
And that's really what we wanted for this table.

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:28.000
Okay.

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:33.000
As a final thing, we're going to make quite a few more tweaks with tab options.

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:35.000
As I mentioned before in the slides,

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:40.000
there's a huge number of options for changing many parts of the table all at once.

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:44.000
You can, for example, change the font sizes for different locations of the table.

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:49.000
In this case, the source notes, I'll make that small, extra small in this case.

00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:52.000
Background colors you can change for different parts of the table.

00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:54.000
And you can change the table font size that way as well,

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:56.000
and reducing it quite a bit.

00:22:56.000 --> 00:22:59.000
So upon running this, we get a much smaller table

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:01.000
where everything's a little bit more condensed.

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:04.000
But we still see that we have lots of color within the table.

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:07.000
It looks pretty much like the table we have in the slides.

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:12.000
If we just were to move down a little bit or uncollapse it.

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:14.000
I'll run this one more time.

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:19.000
You can see the entire table right here, which does match what we have in the slides.

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:23.000
So that's pretty much what I wanted to show in this code along for the third table,

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:26.000
which is the power generation table.

